To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the `window.open()` method with the "save as" option and provide the URL of the file you want to save. Here's an example:

```javascript
const content = "This is some sample text.";
const link = document.createElement("a");
link.href = URL.createObjectURL(new Blob([content]));
link.download = "sample-text.txt";
link.click();
```
In this example, we create a `Blob` object containing the text content and use `URL.createObjectURL()` to generate a URL that points to the blob. We then create an `<a>` element with this URL as its `href`, set the `download` attribute to the desired file name, and trigger a click event on the link using `link.click()`. This will open a "save as" dialog box where the user can choose where to save the file.

Note that this approach requires the user to manually initiate the download, so it may not be suitable for situations where you need to automatically save data without user intervention. Additionally, some browsers may have security restrictions that prevent this method from working in certain scenarios. In those cases, you may need to use other approaches such as server-side scripting or browser extensions to achieve your goal.
